ory:1666 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Lists of members of learned societies]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1660s]]\n[[Category:Scientific organizations established in 1666]]\n[[Category:Members of the International Council for Science]]\n", "name_user": "Mjtth9", "label": "safe", "comment": "edited a typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Academy_of_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "Metropolitan District Commission of Connecticut", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Metropolitan District Commission of Connecticut\n| logo = \n| type = Public Utility\n| genre = \n| foundation = [[Hartford, CT]] (1929)\n| founder = \n| location_city = \n| location_country = \n| location = \n| locations = \n| area_served = [[Greater Hartford]]\n| key_people = William A. DiBella, Chairman\n| industry = Water and Sewage\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| slogan = \n| homepage = {{url|https://themdc.org}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n'''The Metropolitan District Commission of Connecticut''' ('''MDC''') is a public non-profit [[municipal corporation]] chartered by the [[Connecticut General Assembly]] in 1929 to provide [[drinking water]] and [[Sewerage|sewer]] service to the [[Greater Hartford|Hartford area]]. The original agreement tied together the water systems of [[Hartford]], [[Bloomfield, Connecticut|Bloomfield]], [[Newington, Connecticut|Newington]], [[Wethersfield, Connecticut|Wethersfield]], and [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History |url=https://www.themdc.org/about-us/history |website=themdc.org |publisher=Metropolitan District of Connecticut |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>The MDC towns that currently receive water and sewer (referred to as Member Towns) are Bloomfield, East Hartford, Hartford, Newington, Rocky Hill, West Hartford, Wethersfield and Windsor. In addition, the MDC supplies drinking water to East Granby, Farmington, Glastonbury, Portland and South Windsor. The MDC is run by a 29-member board of commissioners; 17 of which are appointed by the member towns, eight by the governor, and four by legislative leaders. The current Chairman of the MDC Board is [[William A. DiBella]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Board Members |url=https://themdc.org/district-board/board-members |website=themdc.org |publisher=MDC |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Nepaug Dam allows water to flow into the Nepaug Reservoir.jpg|thumb|The Nepaug Dam]]\n[[File:Spill way of Saville Dam Barkhamsted clicked by me (Ashutosh) 2.png|thumb|Spill way of Saville Dam Barkhamsted]]\nThe MDC began acquiring land for the planned Barkhamsted Reservoir two and a half years before its charter was granted. in 1932 under Chairman Charles Goodwin the MDC was forced to slow its land acquisition as a result of the [[great depression]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Kevin |title=A Valley Flooded to Slake the Capital Region\u2019s Thirst |url=https://connecticuthistory.org/a-valley-flooded-to-slake-the-capital-regions-thirst/ |website=connecticuthistory.org |publisher=Connecticut Historical Society |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the MDC began work on The South Hartford Conveyance and Storage Tunnel, the largest project in the District's history. The 18ft diameter tunnel will extend four miles at a depth of over 200ft and will carry stormwater during significant rain events, this project is the cornerstone of a larger sewer-stormwater separation project aimed at improving water quality in [[Wethersfield Cove]], the [[Connecticut River]], and [[Long Island Sound]]. The South Hartford Conveyance and Storage Tunnel project has an estimated budget of over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Skahill |first1=Patrick |title=Tunneling 200 Feet Underneath Connecticut For Cleaner Water, At A Cost |url=http://wnpr.org/post/tunneling-200-feet-underneath-connecticut-cleaner-water-cost |website=wnpr.org |publisher=WNPR |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reservoirs== \n[[File:Woods of Rochambeau campsite in West Hartford, August 27, 2008.jpg|thumb|Woods of Rochambeau campsite in West Hartford, August 27, 2008]]\n[[File:LakeMcdonoughFromTunxisTrail.jpg|thumb|Lake Mcdonough from Tunxis Trail]]\nThe Barkhamsted Reservoir was created with the completion of the [[Saville Dam]] on the [[Farmington River]]. The Barkhamsted Reservoir has a filled volume of 36.8 billion US gallons (139,000,000 m3) and is the largest impoundment on the Farmington River system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Kevin |title=A Valley Flooded to Slake the Capital Region\u2019s Thirst |url=https://connecticuthistory.org/a-valley-flooded-to-slake-the-capital-regions-thirst/ |website=connecticuthistory.org |publisher=Connecticut Historical Society |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The reservoir was completed in 1940 at a cost of $10 million.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Water for Hartford|last=Murphy|first=Kevin|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-8195-7080-2|location=|pages=234\u2013237}}</ref> Filling the reservoir destroyed much of the town of [[Barkhamsted Hollow]]. Water from the Barkhamstead Reservoir is transferred by pipes to filtration stations in West Hartford and Bloomfield using only the force of gravity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McGrath |first1=Kaitlyn |title=A Look at Where MDC Gets Your Water |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/weather/stories/A-Look-at-MDC-Water-Treatment-and-Delivery-406326175.html |website=nbcconnecticut.com |publisher=NBC Connecticut |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[West Hartford Reservoir|West Hartford Reservoirs]] are a series of five reservoirs and a number of ponds and water tanks in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web |title=West Hartford Reservoirs Map |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/Recreation/WHtrailsMapWeb_12_2013.pdf |website=themed.org |publisher=The Metropolitan District |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The [[Revolutionary War Campsite]] is a historic archaeological site located on MDC land near Reservoir #6.<ref>{{cite web |title=Revolutionary War Campsite |url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/AssetDetail/NRIS/86000853 |website=nps.gov |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nepaug Reservoir]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Nepaug Reservoir |url=https://newhartfordcthistory.org/2012/03/07/the-nepaug-reservoir/ |website=newhartfordcthistory.org |publisher=New Hartford Historical Society |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nLake McDonough and Hogback Reservoir<ref>{{cite web |title=THE NEPAUG STORY (Burlington version) |url=http://www.cantonmuseum.org/nepaug.html |website=cantonmuseum.org |publisher=The Canton Museum |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Headquarters==\nThe current MDC headquarters on the corner of Main and Wells in [[Downtown Hartford]] was built in the late 1970s and has ~60,000 square feet of floor space.<ref>{{cite web |last1=GOSSELIN |first1=KENNETH R |title=MDC Eyes Building For Hartford Headquarters Expansion |url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-09-11/business/hc-mdc-headquarters-expansion-20130911_1_office-space-parking-lot-new-headquarters |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Its [[brutalist]] facade matches the design language of neighboring buildings.\n\n==Metropolitan District Commission Police==\nThe MDC has its own police force to enforce the law and protect its various operations. According to the MDC use of its facilities is \"regulated by the Connecticut Department of Public Health (Section 24-43c of the Connecticut General Statutes) and enforced by MDC police.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Reservoirs |url=http://themdc.org/recreation-areas/reservoirs |website=themdc.com |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> The current Chief of Police of The MDC Police is Henry Martin.<ref>{{cite web |title=CHIEFS DIRECTORY |url=https://www.cpcanet.org/contact/rolodex/?s=t&r=1 |website=cpcanet.org |publisher=Connecticut Police Chiefs Association |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> In 2011 CEO Charles Sheehan stated that Metropolitan District Officers operate both in uniform and in plain clothes, and that they maintain order at the MDC's corporate headquarters in addition to the field facilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=SHEEHAN |first1=CHARLES |title=Ct Consumer Complaint: MDC Layoffs Affecting Service |url=http://ctwatchdog.com/finance/ct-consumer-complaint-mdc-layoffs-affecting-service |website=ctwatchdog.com |publisher=ctwatchdog}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Niagara Bottling Plant===\nIn 2015 the MDC faced criticism over a deal with [[Niagara Bottling]] that provided the first bulk discount since the District began operating. They kept the deal secret until after it had been completed and did not offer a chancellor public comment. The Bloomfield Town Council faced criticism for not consulting or notifying the public of the bottling plant, and a significant tax abatement, until after the deal was made. There have been calls for increased transparency.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mark |first1=Pazniokas |title=Public water, private profits: A fight over MDC\u2019s tap water |url=https://ctmirror.org/2016/03/14/public-water-private-profits-a-fight-over-mdcs-tap-water/ |website=ctmirror.com |publisher=CT mirror |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the MBD Board voted to discontinue the Niagara discount, the change was part of an effort to restore public trust after the scandal over secrecy and lack of public oversight.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goode |first1=Steven |title=MDC Unanimously Votes To Discontinue Discount That Would Have Benefited Niagara Bottling |url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-mdc-discount-water-vote-1206-20161205-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman DiBella=== \nIn 2008 MDC Chairman William A. DiBella was ordered to pay $795,000 in restitution for his key role in a fraudulent investment scheme involving former State Treasurer [[Paul J. Silvester]] and [[Thayer Capital Partners]]. DiBella and his associates were paid kickbacks from Thayer in return for placing money from the Connecticut State Retirement and Trust Fund into their funds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Court Orders William DiBella, Former Majority Leader of the Connecticut State Senate, to Pay Over $791,000 in Connection with Fraud Relating to State Pension Fund |url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2008/lr20498.htm |website=sec.gov |publisher=US Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The scheme unbalanced the State Retirement and Trust Fund portfolio, potentially putting a huge number of State Retirement accounts at risk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahony |first1=Edmund H. |title=DiBella A Stingy Witness: Testimony Adds Little In SEC Suit |url=http://sip-trunking.tmcnet.com/news/2007/05/17/2632406.htm |website=sip-trunking.tmcnet.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nDiBella was MDC Chairman at the time and there have been widespread calls for him to step down, mainly citing his SEC case, the ethics of public office, and the inherent moral corruption of his acts leading to questions about his character.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quinion |first1=Alison |title=Letter to the Editor: Has William DiBella Become a Liability to the MDC? |url=https://we-ha.com/letter-editor-william-dibella-become-liability-mdc/ |website=we-ha.com |publisher=we-ha.com |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The Federation of Connecticut Taxpayer Organizations has added DiBella to their \u201cHall of Shame\u201d of politicians who grossly betray the public's trust in addition to calling for him to be stripped of his MDC position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Shame |url=http://www.ctact.org/default.asp?location=Hall_of_Shame&callcontent=no&buttonname=Hall%20of%20Shame |website=tact.org |publisher=Federation of Connecticut Taxpayer Organizations |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> Fellow MDC Commissioner Mark Pappa stated that \u201cIf this was a publicly traded company this conversation wouldn\u2019t even happen because there\u2019s no question Mr. DiBella would not be sitting here.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stuart |first1=Christine |title=DiBella Survives Ouster Attempt |url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/dibella_survives_ouster_attempt/ |website=ctnewsjunkie.com |publisher=ct news junkie |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Discrimination Lawsuits===\nIn 2016 the MDC paid $350,000 to settle the case Lebert Thomas v. The Metropolitan District et al. It was alleged that the MDC discriminated against Mr. Thomas on the basis of his race. A confidentiality clause was included with the settlement.<ref>{{cite web |title=THE METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COMMISSION  minutes Monday, June 6, 2016 |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/2016%20Minutes/M%20-%20District%20Board%2006_06_16.pdf |website=themdc.org |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the MDC paid $1.5m to settle claims of discrimination against female and minority employees. MDC Chairman William A. DiBella claimed that the settlement was a result of ``The district wanted to get this behind them.\u2019\u2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=BUDOFF |first1=CARRIE |title=Mdc Pays $1.5 Million To Settle Suit Charged With Discriminating Against Women, Minorities |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-03-15/news/0203151793_1_mdc-discrimination-settle |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> A jury in 2000 had awarded the plaintiff, Sharon Harper, $4.6m after finding that MDC officials had defamed her. The Officials spread rumors about Harper that were of a sexual nature and the jury found them to be on their face defamatory, this was seen as highly offensive to Harper because she was a Churchgoer with a conservative southern background. This was the third time in eight years that the MDC was found to be at fault for discriminating against minority employees.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simpson |first1=Stan |title=Agency Needs To Look Within |url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-09-20/news/0009202634_1_mdc-defamation-discrimination |website=Courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> Despite the communities it serves being highly diverse the Hartford Courant in 2002 classified the senior management of the MDC as \"overwhelmingly white.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simpson |first1=Stan |title=Mdc Chief May Be Out Sooner Than Expected |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-04-08/news/0204080304_1_anthony-milano-mdc-legal-costs |website=Courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Board of Commissioners==\nAs of June 4, 2018, the MDC Board of Commissioners consisted of:<ref>{{cite web |title=THE METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COMMISSION minutes June, 4 2018 |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/2018%20Minutes/M%20-%20District%20Board%2006_04_2018.pdf |website=themdc.com |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n*Andrew Adil\n*John Avedisian\n*Clifford Avery Buell\n*Luis Caban\n*Daniel Camilliere\n*Donald M. Currey\n*Mary Anne Charron\n*[[William A. DiBella]] (Chairman)\n*Timothy J. Fitzgerald\n*Matthew B. Galligan\n*Peter Gardow\n*Denise Hall\n*James Healy\n*Allen Hoffman\n*Jean Holloway\n*David Ionno\n*Sandra Johnson\n*Kathleen J. Kowalyshyn\n*Gary LeBeau\n*Byron Lester\n*Maureen Magnan (Vice Chairwoman)\n*Alphonse Marotta\n*Whit Osgood \n*Domenic M. Pane\n*Bhupen Patel\n*Pasquale J. Salemi\n*Michael Solomonides\n*Raymond Sweezy\n*Alvin Taylor\n*Michael Torres\n*Richard W. Vicino\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hartford County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Public utilities of the United States]]\n[[Category:Specialist police departments of Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Metropolitan District Commission of Connecticut\n| logo = \n| type = Public Utility\n| genre = \n| foundation = [[Hartford, CT]] (1929)\n| founder = \n| location_city = \n| location_country = \n| location = \n| locations = \n| area_served = [[Greater Hartford]]\n| key_people = William A. DiBella, Chairman\n| industry = Water and Sewage\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| slogan = \n| homepage = {{url|https://themdc.org}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n'''The Metropolitan District Commission of Connecticut''' ('''MDC''') is a public non-profit [[municipal corporation]] chartered by the [[Connecticut General Assembly]] in 1929 to provide [[drinking water]] and [[Sewerage|sewer]] service to the [[Greater Hartford|Hartford area]]. The original agreement tied together the water systems of [[Hartford]], [[Bloomfield, Connecticut|Bloomfield]], [[Newington, Connecticut|Newington]], [[Wethersfield, Connecticut|Wethersfield]], and [[Windsor, Connecticut|Windsor]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History |url=https://www.themdc.org/about-us/history |website=themdc.org |publisher=Metropolitan District of Connecticut |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>The MDC towns that currently receive water and sewer (referred to as Member Towns) are Bloomfield, East Hartford, Hartford, Newington, Rocky Hill, West Hartford, Wethersfield and Windsor. In addition, the MDC supplies drinking water to East Granby, Farmington, Glastonbury, Portland and South Windsor. The MDC is run by a 29-member board of commissioners; 17 of which are appointed by the member towns, eight by the governor, and four by legislative leaders. The current Chairman of the MDC Board is [[William A. DiBella]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Board Members |url=https://themdc.org/district-board/board-members |website=themdc.org |publisher=MDC |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Nepaug Dam allows water to flow into the Nepaug Reservoir.jpg|thumb|The Nepaug Dam]]\n[[File:Spill way of Saville Dam Barkhamsted clicked by me (Ashutosh) 2.png|thumb|Spill way of Saville Dam Barkhamsted]]\nThe MDC began acquiring land for the planned Barkhamsted Reservoir two and a half years before its charter was granted. in 1932 under Chairman Charles Goodwin the MDC was forced to slow its land acquisition as a result of the [[great depression]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Kevin |title=A Valley Flooded to Slake the Capital Region\u2019s Thirst |url=https://connecticuthistory.org/a-valley-flooded-to-slake-the-capital-regions-thirst/ |website=connecticuthistory.org |publisher=Connecticut Historical Society |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 21st century the MDC has faced criticism for opaque business practices and offering deep discounts to select industrial users without public consultation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Condon |first1=Tom |title=Bottling plant a wake-up call on state water |url=https://ctmirror.org/2016/12/05/bottling-plant-a-wake-up-call-on-state-water/ |website=ctmirror.com |publisher=ct mirror |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> Regulators at PURA have suggested increased transparency and external audits in addition to the MDC's own.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Besthoff |first1=Ben |title=MDC Water Woes |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/troubleshooters/MDC-Water-Woes-232448851.html |website=nbcconnecticut.com |publisher=NBC Connecticut |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the MDC began work on The South Hartford Conveyance and Storage Tunnel, the largest project in the District's history. The 18ft diameter tunnel will extend four miles at a depth of over 200ft and will carry stormwater during significant rain events, this project is the cornerstone of a larger sewer-stormwater separation project aimed at improving water quality in [[Wethersfield Cove]], the [[Connecticut River]], and [[Long Island Sound]]. The South Hartford Conveyance and Storage Tunnel project has an estimated budget of over $500 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Skahill |first1=Patrick |title=Tunneling 200 Feet Underneath Connecticut For Cleaner Water, At A Cost |url=http://wnpr.org/post/tunneling-200-feet-underneath-connecticut-cleaner-water-cost |website=wnpr.org |publisher=WNPR |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reservoirs== \n[[File:Woods of Rochambeau campsite in West Hartford, August 27, 2008.jpg|thumb|Woods of Rochambeau campsite in West Hartford, August 27, 2008]]\n[[File:LakeMcdonoughFromTunxisTrail.jpg|thumb|Lake Mcdonough from Tunxis Trail]]\nThe Barkhamsted Reservoir was created with the completion of the [[Saville Dam]] on the [[Farmington River]]. The Barkhamsted Reservoir has a filled volume of 36.8 billion US gallons (139,000,000 m3) and is the largest impoundment on the Farmington River system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Kevin |title=A Valley Flooded to Slake the Capital Region\u2019s Thirst |url=https://connecticuthistory.org/a-valley-flooded-to-slake-the-capital-regions-thirst/ |website=connecticuthistory.org |publisher=Connecticut Historical Society |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The reservoir was completed in 1940 at a cost of $10 million.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Water for Hartford|last=Murphy|first=Kevin|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-8195-7080-2|location=|pages=234\u2013237}}</ref> Filling the reservoir destroyed much of the town of [[Barkhamsted Hollow]]. Water from the Barkhamstead Reservoir is transferred by pipes to filtration stations in West Hartford and Bloomfield using only the force of gravity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McGrath |first1=Kaitlyn |title=A Look at Where MDC Gets Your Water |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/weather/stories/A-Look-at-MDC-Water-Treatment-and-Delivery-406326175.html |website=nbcconnecticut.com |publisher=NBC Connecticut |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[West Hartford Reservoir|West Hartford Reservoirs]] are a series of five reservoirs and a number of ponds and water tanks in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web |title=West Hartford Reservoirs Map |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/Recreation/WHtrailsMapWeb_12_2013.pdf |website=themed.org |publisher=The Metropolitan District |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The [[Revolutionary War Campsite]] is a historic archaeological site located on MDC land near Reservoir #6.<ref>{{cite web |title=Revolutionary War Campsite |url=https://npgallery.nps.gov/AssetDetail/NRIS/86000853 |website=nps.gov |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nepaug Reservoir]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Nepaug Reservoir |url=https://newhartfordcthistory.org/2012/03/07/the-nepaug-reservoir/ |website=newhartfordcthistory.org |publisher=New Hartford Historical Society |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nLake McDonough and Hogback Reservoir<ref>{{cite web |title=THE NEPAUG STORY (Burlington version) |url=http://www.cantonmuseum.org/nepaug.html |website=cantonmuseum.org |publisher=The Canton Museum |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Headquarters==\nThe current MDC headquarters on the corner of Main and Wells in [[Downtown Hartford]] was built in the late 1970s and has ~60,000 square feet of floor space.<ref>{{cite web |last1=GOSSELIN |first1=KENNETH R |title=MDC Eyes Building For Hartford Headquarters Expansion |url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-09-11/business/hc-mdc-headquarters-expansion-20130911_1_office-space-parking-lot-new-headquarters |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Its [[brutalist]] facade matches the design language of neighboring buildings.\n\n==Metropolitan District Commission Police==\nThe MDC has its own police force to enforce the law and protect its various operations. According to the MDC use of its facilities is \"regulated by the Connecticut Department of Public Health (Section 24-43c of the Connecticut General Statutes) and enforced by MDC police.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Reservoirs |url=http://themdc.org/recreation-areas/reservoirs |website=themdc.com |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> The current Chief of Police of The MDC Police is Henry Martin.<ref>{{cite web |title=CHIEFS DIRECTORY |url=https://www.cpcanet.org/contact/rolodex/?s=t&r=1 |website=cpcanet.org |publisher=Connecticut Police Chiefs Association |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> In 2011 CEO Charles Sheehan stated that Metropolitan District Officers operate both in uniform and in plain clothes, and that they maintain order at the MDC's corporate headquarters in addition to the field facilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=SHEEHAN |first1=CHARLES |title=Ct Consumer Complaint: MDC Layoffs Affecting Service |url=http://ctwatchdog.com/finance/ct-consumer-complaint-mdc-layoffs-affecting-service |website=ctwatchdog.com |publisher=ctwatchdog}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Niagara Bottling Plant===\nIn 2015 the MDC faced criticism over a deal with [[Niagara Bottling]] that provided the first bulk discount since the District began operating. They kept the deal secret until after it had been completed and did not offer a chancellor public comment. The Bloomfield Town Council faced criticism for not consulting or notifying the public of the bottling plant, and a significant tax abatement, until after the deal was made. There have been calls for increased transparency.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mark |first1=Pazniokas |title=Public water, private profits: A fight over MDC\u2019s tap water |url=https://ctmirror.org/2016/03/14/public-water-private-profits-a-fight-over-mdcs-tap-water/ |website=ctmirror.com |publisher=CT mirror |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the MBD Board voted to discontinue the Niagara discount, the change was part of an effort to restore public trust after the scandal over secrecy and lack of public oversight.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goode |first1=Steven |title=MDC Unanimously Votes To Discontinue Discount That Would Have Benefited Niagara Bottling |url=http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-mdc-discount-water-vote-1206-20161205-story.html |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman DiBella=== \nIn 2008 MDC Chairman William A. DiBella was ordered to pay $795,000 in restitution for his key role in a fraudulent investment scheme involving former State Treasurer [[Paul J. Silvester]] and [[Thayer Capital Partners]]. DiBella and his associates were paid kickbacks from Thayer in return for placing money from the Connecticut State Retirement and Trust Fund into their funds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Court Orders William DiBella, Former Majority Leader of the Connecticut State Senate, to Pay Over $791,000 in Connection with Fraud Relating to State Pension Fund |url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2008/lr20498.htm |website=sec.gov |publisher=US Securities and Exchange Commission |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> The scheme unbalanced the State Retirement and Trust Fund portfolio, potentially putting a huge number of State Retirement accounts at risk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mahony |first1=Edmund H. |title=DiBella A Stingy Witness: Testimony Adds Little In SEC Suit |url=http://sip-trunking.tmcnet.com/news/2007/05/17/2632406.htm |website=sip-trunking.tmcnet.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nDiBella was MDC Chairman at the time and there have been widespread calls for him to step down, mainly citing his SEC case, the ethics of public office, and the inherent moral corruption of his acts leading to questions about his character.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quinion |first1=Alison |title=Letter to the Editor: Has William DiBella Become a Liability to the MDC? |url=https://we-ha.com/letter-editor-william-dibella-become-liability-mdc/ |website=we-ha.com |publisher=we-ha.com |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The Federation of Connecticut Taxpayer Organizations has added DiBella to their \u201cHall of Shame\u201d of politicians who grossly betray the public's trust in addition to calling for him to be stripped of his MDC position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Shame |url=http://www.ctact.org/default.asp?location=Hall_of_Shame&callcontent=no&buttonname=Hall%20of%20Shame |website=tact.org |publisher=Federation of Connecticut Taxpayer Organizations |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> Fellow MDC Commissioner Mark Pappa stated that \u201cIf this was a publicly traded company this conversation wouldn\u2019t even happen because there\u2019s no question Mr. DiBella would not be sitting here.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stuart |first1=Christine |title=DiBella Survives Ouster Attempt |url=https://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/dibella_survives_ouster_attempt/ |website=ctnewsjunkie.com |publisher=ct news junkie |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Discrimination Lawsuits===\nIn 2016 the MDC paid $350,000 to settle the case Lebert Thomas v. The Metropolitan District et al. It was alleged that the MDC discriminated against Mr. Thomas on the basis of his race. A confidentiality clause was included with the settlement.<ref>{{cite web |title=THE METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COMMISSION  minutes Monday, June 6, 2016 |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/2016%20Minutes/M%20-%20District%20Board%2006_06_16.pdf |website=themdc.org |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the MDC paid $1.5m to settle claims of discrimination against female and minority employees. MDC Chairman William A. DiBella claimed that the settlement was a result of ``The district wanted to get this behind them.\u2019\u2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=BUDOFF |first1=CARRIE |title=Mdc Pays $1.5 Million To Settle Suit Charged With Discriminating Against Women, Minorities |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-03-15/news/0203151793_1_mdc-discrimination-settle |website=courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> A jury in 2000 had awarded the plaintiff, Sharon Harper, $4.6m after finding that MDC officials had defamed her. The Officials spread rumors about Harper that were of a sexual nature and the jury found them to be on their face defamatory, this was seen as highly offensive to Harper because she was a Churchgoer with a conservative southern background. This was the third time in eight years that the MDC was found to be at fault for discriminating against minority employees.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simpson |first1=Stan |title=Agency Needs To Look Within |url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-09-20/news/0009202634_1_mdc-defamation-discrimination |website=Courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> Despite the communities it serves being highly diverse the Hartford Courant in 2002 classified the senior management of the MDC as \"overwhelmingly white.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simpson |first1=Stan |title=Mdc Chief May Be Out Sooner Than Expected |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-04-08/news/0204080304_1_anthony-milano-mdc-legal-costs |website=Courant.com |publisher=Hartford Courant |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Board of Commissioners==\nAs of June 4, 2018, the MDC Board of Commissioners consisted of:<ref>{{cite web |title=THE METROPOLITAN DISTRICT COMMISSION minutes June, 4 2018 |url=https://themdc.org/assets/uploads/files/2018%20Minutes/M%20-%20District%20Board%2006_04_2018.pdf |website=themdc.com |publisher=The MDC |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n*Andrew Adil\n*John Avedisian\n*Clifford Avery Buell\n*Luis Caban\n*Daniel Camilliere\n*Donald M. Currey\n*Mary Anne Charron\n*[[William A. DiBella]] (Chairman)\n*Timothy J. Fitzgerald\n*Matthew B. Galligan\n*Peter Gardow\n*Denise Hall\n*James Healy\n*Allen Hoffman\n*Jean Holloway\n*David Ionno\n*Sandra Johnson\n*Kathleen J. Kowalyshyn\n*Gary LeBeau\n*Byron Lester\n*Maureen Magnan (Vice Chairwoman)\n*Alphonse Marotta\n*Whit Osgood \n*Domenic M. Pane\n*Bhupen Patel\n*Pasquale J. Salemi\n*Michael Solomonides\n*Raymond Sweezy\n*Alvin Taylor\n*Michael Torres\n*Richard W. Vicino\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hartford County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Public utilities of the United States]]\n[[Category:Specialist police departments of Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Mdcwater", "label": "safe", "comment": "opinion not fact", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolitan_District_Commission_of_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "Lil Pump discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Lil Pump]]\n| Image           = Lil Pump Fillmore Auditorium 05.01.19 (47761159611).jpg\n| Caption         = Lil Pump performing in May 2019\n| Alt             = \n| Studio          = 2\n| Compilation     = \n| EP              = \n| Music videos    = 16\n| Singles         = 19\n| Option          = \n| Option name     = Mixtapes\n}}\n\nAmerican rapper [[Lil Pump]] has released two [[studio album]]s, twenty-six [[Single (music)|singles]] (including five as featured artist) and sixteen [[music video]]s. In March 2016, Lil Pump released his first single, \"Elementary\". His first single to hit the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot 100]] was \"[[Gucci Gang]]\", debuting at number 81 and later peaked at number 3 on the chart. The single is certified four-times platinum by the [[Recording Industry of America]] (RIAA). In October 2017, he released his [[Lil Pump (album)|eponymous studio album]], peaking at number 3 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Studio albums==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, sales and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\" | Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=BB200>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/lil-pump/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Lil Pump \u2013 Chart History: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US<br />R&B/HH]]<br /><ref name=R&BHH>{{cite web|url=https: